issue.body:
Hello, when adding the nuget package Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Versioning 4.0.0 or 4.1.0, we are hitting the following exception:

> Part URI cannot start with two forward slashes.

This only happens when we use tools like Nuget Package Explorer to download the nuget. It does not seem to happen when consuming directly from Visual Studios. 

It seems this is caused by the same issue as described here: https://github.com/Microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/664 

Any chance we could get a similar fix? Thanks

issue.title: nuget pack can produce invalid packages (OPC files wise) when files have no extension

labels.name: RegressionFromPreviousRTM
labels.description: A regression from the last RTM. Example: worked in 6.2, doesn't work in 6.3

labels.name: Category:Quality Week
labels.description: Issues that should be considered for quality week

issue.body:
## Details about Problem

**Summary:**

dotnet.exe (and probably all other forms of package creation) can produce packages with a malformed [Content_Types].xml when packing files that have no extension and a package path set to / or \\.  In this case, the Override tag will be written with an invalid PartName attribute that starts with // which is expressly forbidden by the opc standard.

Any older version of nuget or other tool relying on System.IO.Packaging is unable to install such a package, like the version of the package manager included in VS 2015.  In these cases System.IO.Packaging usage fails on validation of PartName and throws an exception stating "Part URI cannot start with two forward slashes." which isn't all that helpful to those who encounter it.

This bug has actually bitten a number of unsuspecting package authors, some even from Microsoft, so it would be great to get it fixed sooner rather than later before more invalid packages wind up being produced and available to unsuspecting users.

microsoft/aspnet-api-versioning#587
microsoft/onnxruntime#664
dotnet/aspnetcore#5798
madskristensen/BundlerMinifier#309

**Workarounds:**
1. Give all files an extension or don't pack them
2. Replace PackagePath="/" or "\\" with PackagePath="" (docs currently encourage "\\" increasing the frequency of this issue)

**Environment:**

NuGet product used: VS UI, dotnet.exe

NuGet version: 3.5.0.1484

dotnet.exe --version: 3.1.101

VS version: 2015

OS version: win10 pro v1909 18363.535

## Detailed repro steps

1. Pack a file without an extension and PackagePath="\\" or "/"
2. Observe incorrect Override PartName starting with // in [Content_Types].xml of resulting nupkg.
3. Attempt to install such a package in VS 2015 or use any tool relying on System.IO.Packaging
4. Observe "Part URI cannot start with two forward slashes." error.

### Sample Project

[aspnet-api-versioning v4.1.0](https://github.com/microsoft/aspnet-api-versioning/tree/v4.1.0)

In nuget.props, the LICENSE file is packed by:
`<None Include="$(MSBuildThisFileDirectory)..\LICENSE" Pack="true" PackagePath="\" Visible="false" />` 
That produces the invalid `<Override PartName="//LICENSE" ContentType="application/octet" />` in [Content_Types].xml in the resulting nupkg files.
